Text.Value: There is no greater aberration of His deathly will.
Tell me, saer, if you leave a poisoned cake in a park and a child dies from eating said cake, are you responsible for the child's death?
I cannot believe you truly think that.
Yes, because you should know a child can't resist the temptation.
It is the fault of the gods for not intervening.
Nina fled these grounds in tears. What should be a place of comfort and safety has been ruined by your malevolence.
Oh, yes! But I would use ground glass and razorblades rather than poison.
You showed a grieving child the ways of necromancy. Leave these hallowed grounds now. May Kelemvor have mercy on your soul.
Kelemvor forgive her - there is no sin greater than refusing His deathly will. I shall speak to her - immediately.
Leave these hallowed grounds now.
And for that you have my gratitude - thank you, for doing His work.
How might I be of assistance?
Fear not death, and He shall welcome you.
To think a man lay buried beneath death's soil - it is an abomination of His will. You did well to free him.
You are not welcome here.
Such wisdom. Which means you do not even have the excuse of ignorance.
You walk with death's mantle on your shoulders - your hand as steady as the Lord of the Dead's.

EditorData.logicalname: One off - if you've been nice enough

Text.Value: In part. But the child's parents share the blame.
Kobolds are a festering plague on these hallowed grounds - to disturb the dead is to invite divinity's wrath. Thank you for dealing with them.
There's a zombie by one of the tombstones. Should you go kill it? Kelemvor isn't fond of them, right?
I pray you find comfort among the dead, as I do. To rid ourselves of the coils of flesh is a beautiful thing.
You did well to alert me to Nina's folly. While loss is the price of living, it is a high cost for a child to pay. I will do my best to guide her.
Breathe it in - the damp. The decay. The smell is sweeter than roses - for death is a gift worth cherishing.
You will attend to your business here and then leave - for you try the Lord of the Dead's patience.
And for that you are owed thanks - even if I must turn a blind eye to the grave soil that muddies your shoes. You have my gratitude.
I'm good - thanks.
No, the parents are responsible. They should have taught the child better.
Death's blessings upon you - I am Mortarch Scyre, devotee of Kelemvor.
The young girl at the grave is trying to perform necromancy.
You did the girl child and her parents an honour - the dead deserve love and diligence. I shall personally oversee her rites.

Synopsis:
Mortach Scyre, Priestess of Kelemvor, is a kind and gentle older woman (who will also not hestitate to beat your ass). She can come across a little morbid, but that's simply because she is completely at peace with death in a way very few people are. She is like the shephard of the graveyard - guiding and offering help where needs be.
In this dialogue, she reacts to the things you've done to help people around the graveyard (and also to chastise you in the case of Nina, if you help her raise her brother from the dead)
